book.eternal_starlight.preface:
"Look at these flowers! What a fascinating view! view... view..."
"They're echo flowers, they live for thousands of years, repeating, recording and understanding everything they've heard. heard.. heard..."
book.eternal_starlight.main_story:
In ancient times, two races ruled the overworld.
One day, a war broke out between the two, and the war soon came to an end.
The victorious side, in order to completely destroy the defeated side, sent powerful mages together to tear through space, creating a replica of the overworld, imprisoning the defeated side in it and imposing various curses.
As a price for tearing the space, unstable rifts appeared all over the overworld.
Because of the curse, time in this dimension is forever locked in twilight, stars are dying, and ether liquids are falling from the sky.
Perhaps the curse inspired a desire for survival, or perhaps the punishment fostered hatred. Instead of dying out, the banished people built their own civilization, calling themselves the "Starlighters" and focusing on developing magic in the hope that one day they would make a comeback.
Thousands of years passed, and the magical strength of the Starlighters could no longer be underestimated, and they predicted that their civilization would be destroyed by a colossus, which they thought was sent by the civilization of the overworld.
Fearful of facing extinction, they began to intensify the construction of their defenses-giant machines, which possessed massive bodies and amazing strength.
But when everything was ready, an etheric rain, which at the time had been a rare event in a hundred years, threw them into disarray. The ether liquid corrupted the machine, and the out-of-control machine wreaked havoc across the dimension.
In the end, the machine fell, but the damage done could not be reversed.
In a desperate attempt, the Starlighters tried to use an ancient spell to open a portal to the overworld.
They seemed to succeed, a dark, violet-glowing portal opened, and without time to think, the survivors swarmed in.
It was thousands of years, within which Etheric rain became rarer to the point where it no longer occurred, and the Ether gathered into streams. Some plants were tainted with magical elements, becoming very different from their ancestors. A number of explorers who traveled between dimensions have discovered this dimension and were surprised to find that a civilization had existed in it, using a language identical to the ancient language of the overworld, and according to the ancient records therein stories of this civilization have been passed down. Some explorers left their mark, and some chose to settle in this beautiful dimension.
No one knows where the Starlighters ended up, and the various details of this race have become murky. As the rifts in the overworld gradually closed, the explorers sealed the power contained in the rift within a crystal sphere and guarded it closely to ensure that only the brave and righteous could enter.
book.eternal_starlight.starlight_golem:
Mechanical creations built by the ancient Starlighters to do the bidding of the mechanical giants used to defend against the doom, once possessing heavy armor and unparalleled strength.
To this day, no intact golems exist.
book.eternal_starlight.lunar_monstrosity: A plant infused with the power of the moon's radiance by an ancient civilization, used to devour the souls of prisoners held in the labyrinth.
Only fire can destroy this monstrosity.
book.eternal_starlight.twilight_gaze: Twilight Gaze are known for their glowing purple eyes - in the Abyss, where they originate from, these eyes help them see their surroundings in total darkness. They love the environment of the Abyss, and will attempt to return to it if they stray too far from it. This fish will not actively attack humans, but if you harm them, the Twilight Gaze will not hesitate to fight back.
book.eternal_starlight.shimmer_lacewing: An insect that flits around shimmer river and dark swamp with four pairs of glowing blue or purple wings. Their presence is neither threatening nor useful to other creatures. When the Starlight civilization still existed, this was a small creature loved by children.
